    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about muscle growth and saw two different terms: mechanical tension and metabolic stress. can u explain the difference between them and which one is more important for hypertrophy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanical tension and metabolic stress are two key drivers of muscle growth, but they represent different stimuli. Mechanical tension is the sheer physical force placed on the muscle fibers during a lift, which is the primary mechanism for initiating muscle damage and signaling growth. Metabolic stress, on the other hand, refers to the accumulation of byproducts like lactate within the muscle during intense, high-volume training. While both contribute, the consensus is that mechanical tension is generally considered the more crucial factor for maximizing hypertrophy, especially when training heavy.",
      "source": "target",
