    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if tension is the main thing, how does that actually work on a cellular level? like what's actually happening inside the muscle when that tension is applied?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When mechanical tension is applied, the increased load triggers a series of signals within the muscle fiber, primarily involving the mechanotransduction pathway. This process essentially translates the physical stress into a biochemical signal that tells the cell to adapt and grow. This signaling cascade activates molecular pathways, like mTOR, which is the master regulator for protein synthesis. In essence, the tension tells the muscle cell, \"I need to be stronger to handle this load,\" prompting it to build more contractile proteins.",
      "source": "target",
